Unfortunately, I don't think it's as simple as default or non-default. People disagree about what a default setup is because it's a scale; changing just the icon theme, on its own, would still be considered a default by many, but what about the icon theme AND the WM config? What about icons, wm, fonts and shell changes? For some, even that isn't enough. The number of changes required for a setup to be considered non-default varies from person to person, and will change over time as their tastes and the subreddit develop.
Personally, I don't care what the actual customisations are, as long as I haven't seen it many times before. It doesn't all have to be OC, but most people like variety, and near-default setups are the most popular among new users. I can't think of an easy way to fix this, but continuing to educate the community will help. If everyone looked at what others are posting and avoided posting similar setups, I think these problems would go away.
Basically, take my responses this survey with a (large) grain of salt. No single item on that list will make me consider a setup non-default.

It's tricky because I think that a setup where the only thing changed is an icon theme or something should still count as default, but if there are enough of these little changes, it's pretty obviously not default. So I don't know where to draw the line there. Sorry that this isn't constructive, but I'm sure you guys will come up with a reasonable policy.
Tell and teach people to actually configure their font rendering. Please. I cringe every time I see unhinted, un-antialiased fonts in whatever browser people are using. ;~;

I started filling this out, but tbh, it just isn't this simple. Ricing your setup is a combination of the above. Changing your GTK theme alone means shit, but that, plus a wall, plus some extensions that help your workflow, plus a kickass custom terminal scheme. Creativity is just so subjective. 
I feel the biggest problem is not understanding what ricing is. That its a complicated series of configuration modifications, additions, and creative solutions to a particular task (that very well may only exist in your world) with the addition of making it asthetically pleasing to look at; such as matching wall colors, with term colors, consistent fonts, etc. Its the whole package. What's going on underneath, the scheme itself, and the workflow.  
Another area is that configs, ideas, all of that should inspire further creativity and new ideas. Molding someone's elses solution to work as a solution for you by getting that AHA moment seeing a way they did something. So in short, cloning someone elses git and straight up using all the configs does not make it a good ricing job.
And I guess lastly, the time spent making some of these amazing sesktops. I don't always get the feeling that is understood, that there are many of us who genuinely work really hard at creating our 'masterpiece' before posting it. 
So I'll leave it at that. I just vomited out a rant. Sorry.

What actually makes a non-default setup is the *combination* of several of the points you listed. For example with Xfce, if you only change the wallpaper, or only change the GTK theme, it will still be a default setup. However, if you change the wallpaper AND the GTK/icon theme AND the panel arrangement then it's a non-default.

Same goes for WMs like i3, only putting up a wallpaper or only changing border colors doesn't make it non-default. The combination of wallpaper, borders, bar setup, terminal colorscheme and fonts makes it non-default.

The list of features that make a non-default set-up should be mixed. What I mean by that is that, whilst say a GTK theme on its own doesn't really make a non-default (say Ubuntu GNOME stock but with just the GTK theme changed), changing say the GTK theme, icon theme, browser theme and wallpaper would make a setup non-default. No one change is really sufficient to make a setup non-default, but a number of changes.
